data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The EF Core Cosmos DB provider **removes the sync-over-async bridge entirely**. The opt-in you had in .NET 10 (`EnableSyncOverAsync()` or equivalent) no longer exists. Every synchronous LINQ operator — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()` — and `SaveChanges()` will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime.

## The fix: go fully async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
1. Return `Task<T>` (or `Task` for void) from every data-access method
2. Replace `ToList` → `ToListAsync`, `First` → `FirstAsync`, `Count` → `CountAsync`, `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`
3. `await` each call and mark methods `async`
4. Propagate `async` up through all callers (controllers, services, etc.)

The underlying Cosmos DB SDK is inherently async; the sync bridge was always wrapping async calls with `.Result`/`.GetAwaiter().GetResult()`, risking threadpool starvation. .NET 11 removes that escape hatch entirely.
